  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>THE BLOOD OF LIFE</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=windows-1252">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 4.0">
<meta name="ProgId" content="FrontPage.Editor.Document">
<title>The Blood of Life By Taiba</title>
</head>

<body>

<font SIZE="2">
<p>The Blood of Life</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&quot;Think back to your earliest memory. What is it that you see? Family?
Friends? How would you like to see, instead, the blood of your loved ones
seeping in to the ground beneath their lifeless corpses? Now begone or I shall
share MY memories with you...&quot; With that, she pitched her axe over her
shoulder, sat down, and stared out across the water. The young Dark Elf, who
made the mistake of begging from her, quickly scampered off.</p>
<p>As she sat there, she focused on her thoughts. She thought about her father.
Her brow furrowed. She thought about her mother. Her hand gripped her axe more
firmly. As memories of her past darted about her mind a dark aura surrounded her
whole body. She stood up and began walking down the riverbank, her mind a flurry
of thought. Out of the corner of her eye she saw something moving through the
trees.</p>
<p>She spun around and readied her axe. Standing in front of her now was a tall,
pale man with blonde hair. As he began to speak, the aura around her grew. She
closed her eyes; the image of the man was burning in her eyes as she remembered
what had happened before; long ago, when she was just a child...</p>
<p>************************************************************************</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&quot;Taiba, dinner!&quot; her mother called to her. She got up from where
she was playing in the forest and ran quickly through the trees, back to the
camp where her parents were stationed. She ran up and gave her mother a hug and
sat down next to her father. Around the table were the others who were also
stationed here, far away from their home in Neriak. &quot;It's a dirty
job,&quot; they would say, &quot;but somebody has to do it.&quot;</p>
<p>After dinner, Taiba began playing with the other children who were here with
their parents as well. They were a little older than her but everyone got along.
Her best friends were Minara and Dravidar. Minara would tell her, &quot;One day,
we'll all be going back to Neriak. Then we can finally get out of this ugly
forest!&quot; Taiba didn't think the forest was all that terrible; then again,
she was just a baby when her parents were first assigned to this little camp in
the greater part of the Faydark. She tried to remember what Neriak looked like,
but couldn't. The tiny part of the Faydark near the camp was all she knew.</p>
<p>That night, as she lay in her bed, Taiba tried to piece the dinner
conversation together. All the officers stationed here were all talking so fast
that she couldn't understand everything. She remembered something about
reinforcements and then something about finding silver in the woods. She
wondered what it all meant. It must have been important though, as everyone
seemed concerned about it. Maybe they were sending new people to the outpost.
Maybe even replacements! Her thoughts turned to those of Neriak as she imagined
the homecoming they would all have. She soon drifted in to sleep.</p>
<p>Taiba was jolted awake by the sound of sword fighting and screams. It was
dark inside the tent, but she could see that there was a fire outside. She
jumped out of bed and ran to the opening of the tent. She stopped and gazed upon
the terrible sight before her. There was blood everywhere! There were bodies on
the ground that belonged to some of her fallen Teir'Dal brothers and sisters.
She could hear fighting behind the other tents. She was about to go over to see
what was happening when she saw her mother lying on the ground.</p>
<p>She ran to her mother's side; she was barely breathing. Her mother turned her
head slowly and looked at Taiba. Taiba reached for her mother's blood stained
hand and grasped it firmly in her own small hands. A smile smoothed across her
mother's face. Taiba watched, silently, as her mother took a deep breath and
closed her eyes. Tears began to form in Taiba's eyes as she whispered,
&quot;Good-bye&quot;. Suddenly, Taiba felt as if she were being watched.</p>
<p>&quot;Aw, did you lose your mommy, little miscreant?&quot; said a man's
voice. Taiba raised her head to see a tall, pale man standing in front of her.
He was wearing ornate silver and gold armor and held a short sword in his hand.
Blood was running down the blade as he stuck it in the ground and leaned against
it nonchalantly. Taiba just stared at him with tears streaming down her cheeks.
&quot;Why are you crying? Here, I was under the impression that creatures like
you felt nothing but hatred. Don't tell me you loved your mother...&quot; He
snickered softly to himself. Still, Taiba said nothing. &quot;Well? Aren't you
going to say anything? You should answer someone when they ask a question.&quot;
The man frowned at Taiba's continued silence. He grabbed up his sword and held
it up to Taiba's neck. &quot;Will you speak now? Are you going to plead for your
life like the others?&quot;</p>
<p>Just then, more of the pale skinned men walked up. One of them saluted and
said &quot;Captain, the battle is won. We have taken any survivors as prisoners.
Awaiting your next command, sir.&quot;</p>
<p>The man they called &quot;Captain&quot; withdrew his sword and turned to
them. &quot;Very good,&quot; he said, &quot;Take this one as well.&quot; As two
of the men picked Taiba up and carried her off, she saw the Captain smiled at
her and then proceeded to clean his blade on her mother's shirt. The men who
took her bound her hands as well as her legs, and she was placed inside a wagon
along with some others who hadn't been killed. Minara was there, but Dravidar
was nowhere to be seen.</p>
<p>&quot;Taiba! You're alive!&quot; exclaimed Minara, &quot;Where is Dravidar?&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;I...I don't know. M...my...mother...&quot; Taiba began.</p>
<p>&quot;I'm so sorry, Taiba,&quot; Minara looked down sadly, &quot;They killed
my parents too.&quot; Fresh tears welled up in Minara's eyes. Just then, Taiba
heard a whisper. Taiba and Minara both looked over from where it came. There was
Dravidar, hiding behind a tree! He motioned for them to be quiet. He looked
around to see if the coast was clear. All of the pale men were in the camp going
through the tents, save one by the horses. Now was his chance. Dravidar quietly
crept up to the back of the wagon. He looked around once more and then jumped up
and started untying Minara. She was soon free from her binds. He told Minara to
hide in the trees while he began untying his mother. He had just finished
untying his mother when they heard the voices of the pale men coming closer.
Dravidar and his mother ran from the wagon, back in to the trees.</p>
<p>A couple of the men got atop the wagon while others got on their mounts. The
order was given to move out. The wagon began moving away from the camp. Taiba
looked desperately at the trees, waiting for Dravidar to come back for her, but
as the wagon continued to move she realized he wasn't coming for her; she felt
betrayed. She looked toward the camp that she had called her home. She could see
the blood on the tents as they burned to the ground. She saw a glimpse of her
father's body as well, run through with a long sword.</p>
<p>Just then the Captain and his mount obstructed her view. &quot;Well now, what
do you have to say now?&quot; he asked her. Taiba just stared right through him
without saying a word. He laughed at her defiance and said, &quot;Don't worry,
we have plans for you.&quot; With that, he rode on ahead to lead the wagon.
Taiba lowered her head as tears began to flow down her cheeks.</p>
<p>By that evening, they arrived at their destination. A huge wall in the side
of a hill marked the entrance to the pale ones' city. Taiba and the others were
unloaded from the wagon, their ropes replaced with shackles. They were then
forced to march inside the city that would be their prison. They were ushered in
to several cells, the doors slammed behind them and locked. Taiba was pushed in
to her cell by one of the guards. She tripped over her leg shackles and fell to
the ground. The guards started laughing as she picked herself up and brushed the
dirt off. She didn't say anything, just looked down and sat down on the small,
rickety cot that was to be her bed. The guards walked off laughing and talking
in a strange tongue she could not understand.</p>
<p>Several days passed and she was still alone in her cell. She began wondering
if this was to be the rest of her life. Her parents were gone, her friends had
abandoned her...no one even knew they were in trouble, save the others who had
been captured as well. She looked over at the plate that had been shoved through
the bars earlier; some old bread and a small cup of water. She looked at it and
remembered her mother's cooking. She started to cry, but no tears came. She had
cried so much already, there was nothing left.</p>
<p>Her mourning was interrupted by a commotion at the entrance to the prison.
There were several guards and a couple other men. She heard the Captain’s
voice say, &quot;There are some more down here. Follow me, I'll show you.&quot;
The men started walking down her row, stopping at several cells and quietly
discussing something. The Captain walked to Taiba's cell. &quot;Why, hello
again, my little jail bird. How do you like your new home?&quot; he inquired. He
chuckled, as she said nothing. &quot;Well, we have a surprise for you and your
friends. Looks like you're getting a new home.&quot; He turned to the men who
had come up behind him and said, &quot;This one will do nicely. You don't even
have to worry about her talking back!&quot; They all laughed.</p>
<p>Taiba looked at the two men, they appeared to be merchants but she hadn't
seen anything like them before. One of the men was quite tall with dark skin,
not like her skin though. The other was the exact opposite. He was shorter than
she was and had quite a stocky build and a big nose. She watched as they walked
back down the row. So what was to become of her now?</p>
<p>She had got no sleep since being imprisoned. Instead, she would sit in the
back of her cell and stare at the darkness. The shadows on the wall seemed to
reach out to her as if to welcome her. She would watch the shadows dance like
this all night. When the light came, she would look to the wall for the same
dark shadows that kept her company in the night, but they were not there.</p>
<p>That night the shadows seemed to play out a scene as she watched. She saw
people building a beautiful city and the prosperity that followed. They spread
out all over the lands as they grew. She saw the father of the people smiling
down upon his children. As she watched, Taiba thought of her own father. She
thought about how serious he had been the night before the attack. Had he known
what was coming?</p>
<p>Morning came quickly and soon many guards were about, opening cells and
escorting prisoners out. They came and took Taiba from her cell and pushed her
toward the entrance. Outside she was put in a line with many of the others from
her camp, and also ones she had never met. They were then marched to a small,
wooden stage constructed in the marketplace. There were many people of all sorts
gathered about. She wondered what was going on. Once they were all on the stage,
the tall, dark man from the previous day got up on stage and pulled one of the
captives forward. &quot;I'll start the bidding at two silver pieces! Do I hear
two silver pieces?&quot; he shouted out to the crowd. People began yelling out
and the man would point to them and then ask again. It all went by so quickly
until he said, &quot;Sold! Sold to the gnome in the leather armor for eight gold
pieces!&quot; The prisoner was then escorted off the stage and his shackles
removed, only to be replaced by new shackles that this &quot;gnome&quot; had
brought.</p>
<p>This went on for some time. Each time, a prisoner was brought forward. Each
time, there was yelling and pointing. Each time, the prisoner was taken off the
stage. Before she knew it, Taiba was pulled forward. She felt a hundred eyes
staring at her. The tall man began his yelling, &quot;Ah, here we have a nice
young one. Doesn't talk back, and still young and impressionable; I'd say about
6 or 7 cycles. This one would be excellent for your small, odd jobs. Do I hear
one silver? One silver....do I hear two?&quot; Back and forth it went, people
yelling and pointing.</p>
<p>Then a voice rose above the others, &quot;Fifty gold pieces!&quot; Everyone
stopped and looked to see who had bid that amount. Taiba searched the crowd
herself.</p>
<p>&quot;Fifty gold pieces! Any takers?&quot; he paused. &quot;No? Okay, sold to
Captain Silverwind for fifty gold pieces!&quot; exclaimed the tall man next to
her. As he said that, Taiba locked eyes with the Captain. He had a little grin
on his face. Still in shock as to what had just occurred, she was pushed off
stage. Captain Silverwind, as she now knew he was called, came over to collect
her.</p>
<p>As he was exchanging her shackles he said, &quot;Well, little Jezebel, you
belong to me now. What's that? Nothing to say?&quot; He laughed heartily. After
all the prisoners were sold, the Captain turned to Taiba and said, &quot;Well,
let's get going. I've got a lot of work for you to do.&quot; He grabbed her arm
shackles and proceeded to lead her from the marketplace. The crowd had begun to
disperse. They walked for a ways before the Captain stopped in front of a small
house. &quot;Here's your new home. Let me show you around,&quot; he offered as
he opened the door and pulled her inside.</p>
<p>She looked around and saw the sparse decor of his home. A small stone table,
a couple wooden chairs, a fireplace. There was a large bear pelt on the floor
and two doors leading elsewhere. He turned to her and unlocked the shackles on
her wrists. He hung them on a peg near the door.</p>
<p>&quot;Don't move a muscle, I'll be right back,&quot; he said and put up his
hand. He exited through one of the other doors, only to return in a moment with
a wooden pail and various other items. He handed the items to her and said,
&quot;Now, go and clean the fireplace. It is in need of a good scrubbing.&quot;
He motioned to the fireplace, Taiba just stood there. &quot;Didn't you hear me,
wench? Go clean the fireplace.&quot; Still she remained still. The Captain’s
brow furrowed as he frowned at her. He looked at her a moment, then raised his
hand and hit it across her face, knocking her down. All the cleaning tools fell
to the ground and the bucket spilled its hold across the floor. &quot;Now look
at the mess you've made. You will need to clean that up as well. Now get to work
before I really get angry!&quot;</p>
<p>He sat down in one of the chairs and watched Taiba as she picked herself up
and started gathering the supplies. She cleaned up the spilled water as best she
could and then walked slowly toward the fireplace. The Captain seemed satisfied
with her subordination and grabbed the bucket to refill it. She watched as he
went out the door again and came back with more water. He set it down next to
her and then went through the other door, which appeared to be the bedroom.</p>
<p>He came back an hour later to inspect her work. He was displeased with the
job and said, &quot;Don't you know anything!? This isn't clean. You have to
scrub it.&quot; He grabbed her wrist, put a brush in her hand and pushed it down
on the stone of the fireplace. He moved her hand back and forth until he was
satisfied that she understood how to do it. Taiba continued to scrub and the
Captain walked over and sat down again. He stared at her as she cleaned the
entire fireplace to his standards.</p>
<p>When she was done, he grabbed a piece of bread off of the table and offered
it to her. She accepted it, her hands covered in soot. While she sat and ate the
meal that seemed to be her normal provisions, the Captain looked down at her and
frowned. He heaved a sigh and said, &quot;I suppose we should clean you
up.&quot; Taiba looked down at herself; she still had on the same clothes she
had when she was captured, her mother's blood a permanent reminder of that day's
events. Taiba saw the bloodstains and closed her eyes as she thought about her
mother's last moments.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Captain Silverwind interrupted by grabbing Taiba and dragging her out the
back door. He grabbed a large water bin and set it down in the yard. He filled
it with water from the well as Taiba stood there. He walked over to her and took
the blood stained clothes off of her and threw them in to a pile with other old
rags. He picked her up and put her in the water. She shivered at the coldness of
the water. He laughed and said, &quot;I don't ever think we'll get you clean
enough. Looks like you were just born dirty!&quot; Taiba looked down at her own
dark skin as the Captain's pale white hands scrubbed her clean. She didn't see
anything wrong with her skin.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>When he had got all the blood and dirt off, he went inside the house and
grabbed an old tunic. He picked Taiba up out of the water and put it on her.
&quot;Well,&quot; he said as he considered her, &quot;I guess it's an
improvement.&quot;</p>
<p>It was getting late now and the sun was making its decent in to the trees.
The Captain walked back in to the house again and returned with an old, moth
eaten blanket. He handed it to her and led her over to a corner of the yard.
Taiba saw a large pole in the ground with a single shackle attached to it. He
picked up the shackle and put it around her ankle, then removed the other set
from her legs. He picked up the old pair of shackles and hung them over his
shoulder and began to walk inside. &quot;Get some rest,&quot; he said, &quot;I
have more work for you in the morning.&quot; He walked through the door and
closed it behind him. Taiba was left, standing there, all alone.</p>
<p>Taiba dropped the blanket on the ground and sat down. She looked around the
small yard and then up toward the sky. The stars were beginning to come out. She
watched as the world around her got darker and darker. Patches of light were
replaced with shadows. Taiba stared at the shadows, again, all night; their ebon
arms reaching out to embrace her.</p>
<p>************************************************************************</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&quot;What's a girl like you doing out in the middle of the forest all
alone?&quot; inquired the elf in front of her. Taiba opened her eyes to look at
him again. &quot;What's say you and me go back to town an' hit the bar? I'm
buyin'!&quot; He was leering at her as if he had something more than drinks on
his mind.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Taiba clenched her teeth and said, &quot;I would not be caught dead
consorting with the likes of you. You, on the other hand, just might...&quot;</p>
<p>************************************************************************</p>
<p>Years had passed and Taiba was beginning to mature. The last seven years had
not been kind. The Captain would beat her regularly for, what he called,
&quot;being insolent&quot;. He often made a mockery of her continued silence. He
would sometimes bring some of his officers to the house to have a drink and
gamble with him. He was especially cruel during these times and would call her
names and throw things at her. Then he would yell at her to clean it up. He
would usually give her commands in common tongue, yet she had listened to his
other speak for so long she understood him. It was easy to hear the things he
and his officers were saying about her. Taiba longed to escape, but the Captain,
even through all of his drinking, never once forgot to keep her locked up. Many
times, she had tried to pick the lock of her nighttime restraint, but it was old
and rusty and she never got it to budge.</p>
<p>This night, she was alone. He had gone out drinking and would probably be out
all night. Taiba sat down on the blankets she had called a bed for so long and
looked for her shadowy companion. Every night they came to her and welcomed her
to them. The darkness seemed to be the only thing that cared for her at all.
Tonight, it once again began playing out a scene for her. She saw the people
from before, though not prosperous as they once were. She watched as some of the
people changed and began killing the other people. They were mercilessly killing
for no reason. These blood hungry rebels began threatening the very life of the
leader they had once served. Though it was not over yet, and the leader began to
retaliate in order to save his people from destruction. Just as it seemed they
would win at last, the rebels unleashed a hoard of vicious creatures that turned
the tables. They killed the people's leader and with him, any hope of victory.
Taiba watched in disbelief as the rebels and their sinister companions murdered
all but a handful of the people in the once glorious empire. The survivors all
retreated to their home city and waited. They had given up all hope. There was
nothing left to do now, but die.</p>
<p>Suddenly, a light that shone brightly as if to defy the darkness of the night
interrupted the shadowy story. Taiba squinted and looked toward the light, only
to see the Captain at the doorway holding a lantern. After realizing what it
was, she looked away. She knew he was drunk and was fearful of another
unsolicited beating. Her ribs still hurt from where he had kicked her a couple
days before. She hoped, if she paid him no mind, that he would simply go to bed
and leave her alone.</p>
<p>Instead, he walked over to her and held the lantern up near her face. She
shied away from the light. &quot;Whazza matter, girl? Ya don't like th'light?&quot;
he slurred. She averted her eyes and scooted back. He took a step forward and
held the lantern right in front of her face again. She backed up again, her back
now against the side of the house. He laughed, &quot;Ha ha, she's afraid o'
light!&quot; He set the lantern down next to him and kneeled down in front of
Taiba. He started crawling toward her and murmured, &quot;I'll show ya that it's
good. I'll teach ya t'like light...&quot;</p>
<p>He put his big, pale hand on Taiba's leg and rubbed it lightly. Taiba looked
down at the contrast between their skin and it made her sick. She was suddenly
filled with such disgust at the whiteness of his body and she was afraid of what
he was doing. She closed her eyes as his other hand reached out for her waist.
She didn't know what was happening but she hated it. Her hand balled up in to a
fist and swung. It connected with his jaw and he lost his balance. He fell on
his side next to her. She stood up and moved as far away as the chain would
allow.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>He rubbed his jaw and looked up at her. &quot;You little witch,&quot; he
screamed, &quot;You'll pay for your disobedience!&quot; He stood up and stormed
angrily toward her. In a fluid movement that belied his drunkenness, he raised
his hand and smacked Taiba to the ground. He proceeded to kick her and step on
her. Then, she did something she hadn't done since being bought by the
Captain...she began to cry.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>He stopped his assault as he heard the quiet whimpering coming from Taiba.
&quot;So, yer not a mute after all. But don't think that your tears will make
any difference. Whores like you deserve to be punished.&quot; The Captain got
down on his knees next to Taiba and grabbed on to her wrists. He pushed her arms
back above her head and held them there with one hand as the other made its way
down her body.</p>
<p>Taiba was so frightened; she continued to sob uncontrollably as she felt him
yank up on her ragged tunic. She struggled to free herself but couldn't; she was
trapped. The Captain, while still holding her arms, positioned himself over her.
He leaned his head down and bit at her neck; she jumped at the sensation. What
was happening? He continued sliding his other hand down her body. He quickly ran
his hand down her legs and then pulled them apart. She attempted to pull her
legs together but he had already moved in between them. Taiba cried out
piteously as the Captain forced himself upon her, but he paid no attention to
her cries. He moved his body against hers as she focused on the stars.</p>
<p>While he continued to have his way with her body, the lantern was knocked
over and darkness ensued. Taiba looked toward the shadows that had now returned.
She looked pleadingly at the shadows as if they could somehow put an end to
this. The shadows' reply came as a continuation of its murky story. She focused
on the shadows so as to escape the reality of what was happening.</p>
<p>The people now were trapped inside their once prosperous city; those days
were only a memory now. Things seemed dim until one man showed them the way. The
father of the people opened a hole in to the ground and the man led the people
in to it. The tunnel was sealed behind them. When the rebel forces arrived, they
found the city deserted. Their victory was assumed and the city was destroyed.
The father of the people kept his children inside the earth until they could one
day reclaim their empire. Taiba saw the shadowy image of the people's father. He
seemed to be reaching his arms out to her. Her tears then clouded her vision and
he was gone.</p>
<p>The Captain moaned and collapsed on her. He took a couple deep breaths and
then climbed off of her. He stood up and kicked her in the side. Then he
mumbled, &quot;That'll teach you...&quot; and stumbled off inside the house.
Taiba was left there, shivering and afraid. She wiped the tears from her eyes
and curled up in to a ball. She did not sleep that night.</p>
<p>In the morning, things went as they normally did, though the Captain was
slightly more cruel to her. He called her names much more frequently and would
mumble things in his light tongue. The days turned in to weeks. He had returned
to her twice since his initial attack. She no longer cried; she would just stare
deeply in to the shadows. She would try to escape, especially at these times,
but was always overpowered by him. It seemed her tormented life would never
change and she would always live a life of demeaning servitude to this man she
hated so much.</p>
<p>One evening, the Captain brought several of his officers back to the house as
well as another man she did not recognize. He was slightly shorter than the
others, yet his skin was still fairly pale. They were drinking and gambling and
having a good time. The Captain seemed to be losing a lot that day. As the hours
wore on, his winnings dwindled until he had none left.</p>
<p>&quot;You've got nothing left, Silverwind. It appears you're out,&quot; said
the strange man. The Captain wouldn't have it. He looked around to see what else
he could wager as he felt he had a winning hand. He picked up his helm, but one
of his officers reminded him that he would be demoted for such an action. Then
the man piped up, &quot;What about that slave of yours? You could put her up as
a wager.&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;Right!&quot; the Captain exclaimed, &quot;I bet the little, inky
wench.&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;Wonderful, then let's see what you've got, Silverwind,&quot; pressed
the man. The Captain laid down his hand, and it seemed that victory was
inevitable. Then the man laid down his hand.</p>
<p>&quot;How can this be?&quot; The Captain hung his head as his defeat was laid
out on the table.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&quot;Well, Silverwind,&quot; chimed the man, &quot;it appears you've lost.
If you fellows will excuse me, I must be going. Let me just collect my
winnings...&quot; The man put his various winnings in a pouch at his waist and
then turned to a shocked Taiba. &quot;Come on, girl,&quot; he said, &quot;I am
your new master now.&quot; She looked around and then tentatively stepped toward
him. &quot;Hurry up!&quot; He grabbed her arm and pulled her toward him. Then
she followed the man out the door and in to the night.</p>
<p>************************************************************************</p>
<p>The light elf looked slightly confused at Taiba's words, but he did
understand the axe in her hands as she readied herself. &quot;Ah! You're a
feisty one, all right! But if I win, you have to have a drink with me,&quot; he
insisted as he pulled his sword from its scabbard.</p>
<p>&quot;I don't see how that would be possible,&quot; Taiba countered. &quot;If
you win, then I'll be dead.&quot; She gave a wry smile and then motioned for him
to come at her.</p>
<p>He advanced and the sound of metal clashing together rang throughout the dark
forest. He swung down at her, but was blocked by the shaft of her axe. She
pushed on the blunt end of her axe and hit him squarely in the jaw. He staggered
backwards from the blow; a trickle of blood came from a cut above his eye. Taiba
focused on the blood and the aura surrounding her channeled around her hands and
glowed a dull red. He looked confusedly at her as she closed her eyes for a
moment and the reddish aura faded. He held up his sword and came towards her. In
an instant that seemed to last forever, Taiba opened her eyes and held her hands
out. A flash of darkness burst from her hands toward her attacker. The force hit
him and he fell to the ground. The held curled up as he writhed in agony.</p>
<p>Taiba walked up to her subdued attacker and looked down at him in disgust.
His face was contorted in pain and he was barely breathing but he forced himself
to murmur, &quot;Please spare my life...&quot;</p>
<p>She bent over and whispered in his ear, &quot;Your life is meaningless to me.
The only thing that matters is your blood.&quot; His eyes were wide with fear as
Taiba raised her huge twin-bladed axe, &quot;and I will have it!&quot; Bone
crunched as her axe bit down for the final blow, spraying blood over the foliage
and her legs. Wrenching the blade from the now lifeless corpse, she inspected
her work; blood oozed down her axe. It ran down her hand and dripped off the
blade. She focused on the pool of blood forming at her feet. It was as if she
could still hear the crowd cheering.</p>
<p>************************************************************************</p>
<p>Taiba stood over the body of her last opponent as the crowd cheered. She saw
them waving their arms and moving their lips but did not hear them; they were
not important. In her mind, all was silent except for a reassuring voice that
told her she had done well. Taiba stared blankly at the unfortunate slave that
had been her victim; the blood was an all too familiar sight now. She dropped
the rusty short sword at her feet and walked to the arena's exit; she knew the
routine. Blood followed behind her as it ran off of her hands. It could be her
opponents, it could be hers, it could be a mixture of the two, but it did not
matter anymore.</p>
<p>Back down below the arena, she was placed in to a holding pen until her next
battle, or until the day was over. She sat quietly and closed her eyes. Though
it was daytime, she could still see the shadows when she closed her eyes. Over
the past two years, the shadows had begun speaking to her through her mind and
she could now hear the voice more clearly. It no longer told her stories, but
spoke of her directly. As she listened now the voice told Taiba of its pride
from her victory.</p>
<p>Several hours passed and the day came to and end. Taiba had not had to fight
again. She was now loaded up in to a cart with some of the other victors and
taken from the arena. She knew she would be back in a few weeks. She would be
forced to kill to save herself from the same fate. In the arena, there was no
difference between the races. She had killed ones from many races and had
learned much about the other races. She now knew of the tremendous Trolls and
Ogres, as well as the tiny Gnomes. She had gone up against Humans and dark
skinned Erudites. She had even fought several Dark Elves. She learned that
Captain Silverwind was one of the Koada'Dal and her current master, Tralik, was
called Fier'Dal.</p>
<p>At first, Taiba did not want to fight her opponents. It was by a stroke of
luck that she won her first battle. She had been pushed out in to the arena with
a rusty sword and a shield. She didn't know what was going on. She was up
against an impressive looking Ogre who towered over her. He charged at her,
sword drawn. She turned and ran from him but had nowhere to go. Things were not
looking up for Taiba as she ran to the side of the arena and huddled behind her
shield. As the Ogre advanced toward her, the voice told her not to be afraid,
and when the Ogre raised his sword to attack the voice told her to stab with her
sword. The Ogre ran right in to her sword when he stepped forward. Blood poured
from the wound in his belly and Taiba let go of the sword and ran toward the
arena's exit. She pounded on the heavy wooden door to be let out. She looked
behind her to see the Ogre fall over; when she looked back, the doors were
opening.</p>
<p>The more she fought, the less she cared for the life of her opponent. After
she'd got the hang of a sword, she would try to only wound her opponents in
order to win the match. As time wore on, she became accustomed to battle and
began to crave the blood. It was kill or be killed, and she preferred to do the
killing. The voice would help her during these fights to do just that. By the
time she had to fight one of her own, she was too consumed by the blood that she
was numb as to who her opponent was. That battle between her and a fellow Dark
Elf was over quickly. She was undefeated in the arena, mostly due to her thirst
for blood. She had made her master plenty of money from the wagers. It was
because of these things that Tralik called her his Blackhearted Investment.</p>
<p>The journey back to Tralik's habitation was rather long. They arrived the
next morning and the fighters were promptly escorted in to their cells. Tralik
believed that his fighters were more ferocious and were more likely to win him
money if they were kept in solitude, away from society. He had a row of cells in
a small cavern, each with a thick, wooden door and no windows. It was here he
kept his fighters.</p>
<p>Taiba walked in to her cell; the room grew dark as the door was locked behind
her. She sat down in the corner like she always did. She closed her eyes as the
voice began speaking to her. &quot;Taiba,&quot; it called, &quot;what are you
feeling?&quot; She thought about it for a moment. &quot;Ah, hatred. How
wonderful! Do you hate the ones who have slaughtered your family and enslaved
you? Do you want revenge for your family?&quot; Taiba's brow furrowed. &quot;Oh,
I see, you are only after your own revenge. Excellent. Tell me what you have in
mind,&quot; the voice urged. She imagined herself in the arena at Felwithe, as
she now knew the city was called, standing victorious over the body of Captain
Silverwind. A smile touched her lips as she saw the arena and stands filled with
corpses, painting the white marble red with blood. &quot;Be patient,
child,&quot; the voice soothed, &quot;One day we will have our wishes come
true.&quot; Taiba laid down on the cool ground and drifted off to sleep with
thoughts of blood drifting through her mind.</p>
<p>Time crept by, but it eventually came time to leave for Felwithe again. Taiba
and the other fighters were extracted from their dim cells and placed back in to
the caged wagon they all knew too well. Their shackles were checked and the
locks secured. Before you knew it, they were off. Taiba looked at the trees as
they went. The sun broke through in places and filled the forest with a bright
warmth. She hated it. Taiba closed her eyes and tried to forget about the cheery
atmosphere. After all, what did she have to be happy about? Her life had been
nothing but hardships.</p>
<p>Her troubled thoughts where interrupted by the sound of heavy footsteps
approaching. From behind the trees and brush came a score of orcs, all yelling
and waving about their weapons. The wagon came to a halt as the orcs surrounded
them. Tralik stood up at the helm and drew a pair of machetes; the men of his
convoy drew their own weapons as well. &quot;In the name of Crushbone,&quot; one
of the orcs yelled, &quot;surrender your valuables and your slaves!&quot;</p>
<p>Tralik beamed a confident smile and replied, &quot;I'll do no such thing!
You'd best be leaving if you know what's good for you.&quot; With that he jumped
down from the wagon and took a battle stance.</p>
<p>The one orc cried, &quot;In the name of Crushbone!&quot; The other orcs
raised their weapons and ran in to attack. The fighting began as orcs and
Tralik's men fought it out. Tralik, himself, was holding his own against a
number of the orcs. The prisoners could do nothing but watch as the fighting
went on all around them. However, with the clanging of swords, the horses became
spooked and reared up. The wagon jolted forward as they took off. They did not
get far before the horses took them too close to a tree and knocked the wagon
over. The horses continued running as the wagon fell on its side by the tree and
tossed the prisoners about. Taiba saw her chance when some of the bars were
knocked out in the crash. She pushed her way through them and was freed from the
wagon. She was still in shackles though. She needed to get the key from Tralik.
She would have to take them from him, or die trying. She would have to take that
chance, otherwise it meant she would continue her life of slavery. Taiba decided
she'd had enough.</p>
<p>Taiba hurried back to where the fighting was happening. There were bodies on
the ground of both elf and orc alike. Tralik, however, was still standing. He
looked virtually unscathed. She scuffled over to one of the bodies and grabbed a
short sword off of it. She walked between the other fights until she was behind
Tralik. He was busy fighting a couple of the orcs. She could see the keys
dangling from his belt; perhaps this would be easier than she thought.</p>
<p>She ran up behind him and thrust at him with her sword. At last, she thought,
I will be free. She looked up, however, to find Tralik looking at her, his sword
blocking hers. &quot;What's this?&quot; he said. He scowled and turned around
quickly, slashing his swords through the two orcs attacking him. He watched them
fall to the ground and then turned back toward Taiba. &quot;So you think you can
take me on, my little Blackhearted Investment?&quot; Tralik jeered, &quot;Come
on then.&quot; Taiba thrust her sword at him only to have it blocked. Again and
again she tried to hit him but to no avail. He smiled boldly and spun quickly
around, knocking Taiba backwards. She steadied herself and looked up at him. His
eyes were closed and he was chanting softly. As she ran at him again, he opened
his eyes and a strange light started glowing around him. An instant later, Taiba
fell to her knees; her skin felt as if it were on fire.</p>
<p>Tralik swung his twin blades down at Taiba, but she managed to hold up her
sword to block the attack. She got to her feet, her skin still burning. The
fighting continued; their movements were swift. Sometimes the swords found their
mark, other times they missed. They were both bleeding from the wounds created
from the swordplay, though it seemed that for every hit that Taiba managed,
Tralik would get in two or three. She was tiring quickly but continued to put
everything she had in to the fight.</p>
<p>Tralik still seemed confident of his victory and with each blow Taiba
weakened. He began pushing her back. She was tired and hurt, though the burning
was fading from her flesh. It was all she could do to try to block his blows.
Tralik attacked her with one sword, but Taiba held fast. He then raked his other
blade lightly across her knuckles, intent only on spilling more of her blood.
Taiba watched the blood as it cascaded down the hilt of her sword and on to the
ground. Her eyes went blank as she focused on the crimson flow.</p>
<p>In her mind she saw herself standing in a black, barren world where rivers of
blood meandered about. She could see the people of her childhood encampment
drowning in the rivers. Floating above were the soldiers and Captain Silverwind
all laughing as they killed more and more faceless Dark Elves and threw the
bodies in to the river. The river began to overflow and the blood inched closer
to where she was standing. The soldiers' laughter was deafening in her ears; the
blood began lapping at her feet. She covered her ears with her hands and closed
her eyes but could still feel the warmth of the sticky liquid creeping up her
legs. The smell was overwhelming as the blood continued its ascent at an
alarming rate and threatened to engulf her. She lifted her head and let out a
cry as it finally consumed her. She found herself floating through what now
seemed to be an endless ruby ocean. She opened her eyes and looked around.
Through the erubescence she could see a small dark spot coming closer; it was
the shadows coming for her. The shadows swirled around her in the redness before
taking on a form. The shadowy form floated in front of her and held out its
arms, presenting Taiba with a small shadowed orb. Taiba held her hands out to
take it but when she touched the orb, it was to be absorbed in to her body
through her outstretched hands. In that instant, the shadows were gone and her
bloody surroundings were shattered in to blackness.</p>
<p>Taiba was jolted back in to consciousness. The cruelty shown her filled her
mind and hatred consumed her. A dark aura began to shimmer about her body,
eventually focusing on to her hands. She moved without thinking and put her hand
on Tralik's chest. She looked in to his eyes as a flash of strange blackness
came from Taiba's hand and moved in to Tralik's body. He winced as he clutched
his chest in pure agony, but he did not fall.</p>
<p>She was pushed back by the force and tripped on one of the bodies on the
ground. She looked up to see Tralik standing over her. He was out of breath and
still in pain from her dark attack, though he stood there with his sword
pointing down at her. It appeared she had been defeated. She did not regret her
decision, however, as she had given it everything she had; she had known the
consequences. Tralik sneered and slowly raised his sword to deliver the
finishing blow. Taiba closed her eyes; perhaps the shadows would finally welcome
her to them when all was over.</p>
<p>Just then, a blue aura surrounded Taiba. Tralik looked surprised. He halted
his attack and looked around. The aura faded and Taiba felt better as the wounds
faded from her body leaving only the bloody stains as a reminder. She opened her
eyes and stood up, fully rejuvenated. Taiba saw Tralik scowling at something
behind her. She turned to look at what he was focused on. There, standing
slightly behind a tree, were two men in plate armor. One was wearing a golden
plate armor while wielding a shield and caduceus. The other was wearing blue
plate mail, a deadly blade in each hand. It was their helms that caught Taiba’s
attention. Each was shiny silver with the same horned skull design that brought
back memories from her childhood. It was hard to tell at first because of the
amount of metal encasing each man, but there was no doubt about it, these were
Dark Elves.</p>
<p>An expression of anger settled on Tralik's face and he cursed at the two,
&quot;Annoying darkies! I'll teach you to interfere!&quot; He began running
toward the gold clad elf. Taiba caught this out of the corner of her eye and
turned as he ran past her, putting her leg out to trip him. He began to fall and
in one fluid motion, Taiba ran the edge of her sword across Tralik's belly, up
behind, and plunged it in to his back. He landed on the ground with a thud. A
trickle of blood came from his lips as he suffered through his last few breaths.
Taiba let out a cry and pushed the sword in deeper; Tralik's eyes widened and
then he went still. The ground beneath him turned reddish as his blood seeped in
to the forest's floor. It was finally over. She kneeled down next to her
defeated foe and plucked the keys from his belt.</p>
<p>While she was busy unlocking her shackles, some of the orcs wandered back in
to the area after chasing off the rest of Tralik's men. A couple of them
reported to the two Dark Elves standing there and then went out in to the woods
again. After freeing herself, Taiba stood up and found herself face to face with
the two armored men.</p>
<p>The one in gold spoke, his voice conveying no emotion, “You appeared to
need assistance. My Master has healed you.”</p>
<p>“Please!” the other interjected, “Aenril, you healed her, and don’t
play like you are some hero. We have been standing here since the first stroke.”</p>
<p>“I am just a conduit. It is My Master’s will that mended her form,”
responded Aenril. “And Uukrul, I was not holding you back. You could have
killed him at any moment; her too if you wished it.”</p>
<p>“It was her fight,” said Uukrul, his voice suddenly stone cold.</p>
<p>“Nevertheless.”</p>
<p>Aenril turned to face her. “And what are you doing here, Young One? I was
not aware we had one of Innoruuk’s Knights stationed anywhere near Crushbone…at
least not one Dvinn had told us about.” Suspicion filled his voice.</p>
<p>&quot;I...Innoruuk...&quot; Taiba trailed off as she stared at nothing in
particular.</p>
<p>Aenril started again, breaking her reverie, &quot;At any rate, come along and
we'll see what is to be done with you. My brother and I will take you to see
Dvinn.&quot; He and Uukrul began to walk off and motioned for her to come along.
She followed several steps behind them, not entirely trusting of the pair. After
much walking they approached a passage in the side of a hill. They entered in to
the passage, joined by the orcs and other rescued slaves.</p>
<p>It was here, in Crushbone, that the truth about Taiba's tortured past was
revealed. Ambassador Dvinn just nodded as Taiba told her story. She told how the
outpost had been attacked, that she had been captured and forced to live as a
slave for many years. She told of her battles in the arena and of the cruelty of
all she encountered. There were things, however, that she felt did not need to
be mentioned.</p>
<p>When she had said her piece, Dvinn explained to her what happened to the
outpost she had been at so many years ago. When they had not heard word from the
camp for several weeks, scouts were sent out to investigate. By the time they
arrived, most of the evidence had been blown away or dragged off by animals. It
was assumed that there had been an attack by one of their enemies and the three
survivors they found confirmed this. No word had been given after the initial
report and the matter was considered closed. They set up a new outpost, this
time in a less conspicuous area of the Lesser Faydark.</p>
<p>Dvinn got up from where he'd been sitting and walked over to Uukrul and
Aenril. They spoke briefly before Dvinn turned back to face Taiba. &quot;I have
arranged for these two to escort you back to Neriak. You've had a tough time of
it; they'll be sure to watch out for you.&quot; Taiba followed the brothers to a
room where a robed Dark Elf was waiting. When they were ready, the robed Elf
began to cast a spell and opened a portal in the very fabric of space. The three
entered and were instantly transported to a large, ancient looking pyramid in a
forest darker than any other she remembered seeing. Taiba wondered where they
were. Was this home?</p>
<p>After a small walk, they came upon a stone tunnel leading in to the side of a
mountain. There was a large symbol above the guarded entrance that seemed
strangely familiar. Taiba studied it briefly as they walked past the guards and
in to the dark city of Neriak. Inside Taiba was amazed by the difference between
the white, stone walls of Felwithe and the murky city she was now in. The jagged
cavern walls created a copious collection of shadows. She felt this place suited
her.</p>
<p>She followed her escorts through a twist of buildings and tunnels; past shops
and houses. There was a bustle of people around. It was not uncommon to see, in
the mix of people, a fully armored one run past on their way to somewhere
seemingly important. After more distance than Taiba had expected, the trio came
upon a building that was the very shade of the blood that seemed to follow Taiba
around. Aenril stopped before the gates of the building. &quot;Follow
Uukrul,&quot; he instructed, &quot;He will take you the rest of the way. I have
matters to attend to.&quot; He turned and walked off without waiting for a
reply.</p>
<p>A curious look was on Taiba's face; she looked up at Uukrul. &quot;Don't you
mind him,&quot; he laughed. His face then turned serious, &quot;It has occurred
to me, Milady, that you have not spoken as to what you are called. Might you
tell me?&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;Taiba,&quot; was her quick reply.</p>
<p>&quot;Well, Taiba,&quot; he said, &quot;May I be the first to welcome you to
your new home.&quot; He opened the gates to the scarlet building and invited
Taiba to come in. He led her inside the building and in to a great hall. Uukrul
walked over to an impressive looking man in the room and had a quick exchange of
words. The man came to Taiba and thoroughly considered her.</p>
<p>&quot;Taiba, welcome to the Lodge of the Dead. I am Tralon Din`a, guild
master of the Knights of Innoruuk. We will teach you to focus the power that has
been bestowed upon you so that you may help grant our Lord's wish. Learn to walk
the path of darkness and channel your hatred to avenge our mighty Lord.&quot;
Taiba cared little about the revenge of others. She did not refuse, however. She
simply said nothing; she saw this as an excellent chance to learn to become more
powerful so that she could exact her own revenge one day.</p>
<p>Tralon nodded at Uukrul and began leading Taiba out an archway. Uukrul patted
Taiba on the head and casually meandered to the exit. She quietly watched him go
and then turned to follow Tralon. She had now embarked on her path to revenge;
ready to learn techniques and magics to help her become more powerful. She made
a vow at that moment that she would not fail in her quest. She smiled to herself
as she walked out of the room.</p>
<p>************************************************************************</p>
<p>Taiba sat down next to the body of the now less offensive High Elf.
&quot;Taiba,&quot; called the voice, &quot;You grow more powerful every day. But
there are many obstacles we must face on our path. Are you prepared?&quot; Taiba
looked over and watched the blood run down the bank and leave a faded red trail
in the softly rippling water.</p>
<p>She would be ready.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
